<p>One of the main differences between writers and people who want to be writers is that writers just write.Â </p>

<p>Another of of the main differences between writers and people who want to be writers is that the wannabes assume writers know how to express themselves clearly. Writers know that they donâ€™t and yet they write anyway.Â </p>

<p>They are brave enough to vomit bullshit all over lovely, clean pieces of paper. Then they gradually and painfully shape that bullshit into clear, evocative prose.Â </p>

<p>Wannabes falsely believe writers write perfect first drafts. Writers know that first drafts read as if they were written by demented parrots holding pens in their beaks.</p>

<p>Writers donâ€™t even try for perfection in first drafts. They know that perfection comes, as much as it ever does, during countless edits and rewrites.</p>

<p>Sometimes wannabes even know that the key is to write a shitty first draft and then to polish it into gold, but they donâ€™t want to do it. They are egotistical enough to feel they are exempt from writing shitty first drafts. Or they are too lazy to write multiple drafts, and just the thought of having to go back over something many times makes them want to quit. Writers arenâ€™t lazy. They simply do the work. They get on with it.Â </p>

<p>The secret is that our brains are better at reacting than acting. If we have something to react to, we can improve it, react to the improved version, and keep on improving until weâ€™re satisfied. This is why itâ€™s easier to edit someone elseâ€™s text than to write oneâ€™s own. Editing is reacting. This is also why itâ€™s so important to write BAD prose â€“ prose that doesnâ€™t express itself well â€“ so thereâ€™s SOMETHING on the page. Once that something exists, you can react to it, and once you start reacting, the real artistry begins.</p>

<p>The secret is to write badly.Â </p>

<p>Hereâ€™s the best advice about writing Iâ€™ve ever come across:</p>

<p>â€¦ The ego is the enemy of the imagination. Anything that you think about writing when youâ€™re not writing is a product of the ego and is absolutely wrong. One hundred percent, all the time, wrong. And if you take a step back and think how much time you spend trying to purify yourself in order to get ready to write, thatâ€™s like 95% of the time. And the reason for that is the ego has a stake in perpetuating the behavior that youâ€™ve already engaged in. We do not think our way to right action; we act our way to right thinking.</p>

<p>So what I do is I start writing. If I think about my writing before I start to write, what Iâ€™m really doing is justifying not writing, because â€¦ Iâ€™m not writing. â€¦ Iâ€™m going to find a way to keep not writing. So what I say is I donâ€™t have the idea yet; itâ€™s not fully realized yetâ€¦ Not only that: I donâ€™t have pencils; my pencils are not sharpened; I donâ€™t have the right notebook. â€¦ Whoa! Eleven-forty five already. Time for lunch.</p>

<p>â€¦ When you think about exercising, what you invariably say to yourself is, â€œYou know, Iâ€™m too fat. Whatâ€™s the point? Iâ€™m too old; Iâ€™m too fat; Iâ€™m too old; Iâ€™m too slow; Iâ€™m too this; Iâ€™m too thatâ€¦â€ And all youâ€™re doing is justifying the fact that youâ€™re not exercising.</p>

<p>â€“ David Milch</p>

