<p>Thereâ€™s a trick that I can share with you that I got from Ernest Hemingway.</p>

<p>Hemingway - thereâ€™s a guy who could write a story.</p>

<p>Start Writing like Hemingway
Hemingway! But Hemingway was a genius! He won the Nobel prize for Literature for goodnessâ€™ sake!</p>

<p>True, but even he used to find it difficult to get started on a story.</p>

<p>What chance have we got, when Hemingway struggled?Â  Well, some, because we can learn from the master.</p>

<p>This is what Hemingway said he did:</p>

<p>Sometimes when I was started on a new story and I could not get going, I would sit in front of the fire and squeeze the peel of the little oranges into the edge of the flame and watch the sputter of blue that they made. I would stand and look out over the roofs of Paris and think, â€œDo not worry. You have always written before and you will write now.Â All you have to do is write one true sentence.Â Write the truest sentence you know.â€</p>

<p>Ernest Hemingway, A Moveable Feast</p>

<p>One True Sentence</p>

<p>The idea that what you need to do to get started is write One True Sentence is one that lots of authors and story theorists have used and found to work:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Ernest Hemingway called it one true sentence.</li>
  <li>InÂ Story,Â Robert McKee calls it the controlling idea.</li>
  <li>InÂ The Art of Dramatic WritingÂ , Lajos Egri calls it the premise.
But theyâ€™re all talking about the same thing. What theyâ€™re talking about it is:</li>
</ul>

<p>What you are trying to say.</p>

<p>Call it the truth, call it the controlling idea, call it the premise, what we need to do is think about what we want the reader to come away from the story believing.</p>

<p>We want to change their mind.</p>

<p>Thatâ€™s the question, you see: what do you passionately believe? What makes you want to grab people by the shoulders and shake them until they agree with you? Thatâ€™s One True Sentence.</p>

<p>No idea and no situation was ever strong enough to carry you through to its logical conclusion without a clear-cut premise.</p>

<p>Â Â Lajos Egri, The Art of Dramatic Writing</p>

<p>And because itâ€™s your story, you can metaphorically grab the reader by the shoulders and shake them until they listen.</p>

<p>Storytelling is the creative demonstration of truth. A story is the living proof of an idea, the conversion of idea to action. A storyâ€™s event structure is the means by which you first express, then prove your ideaâ€¦ without explanation.</p>

<p>Robert McKee, Story</p>

<p>So thatâ€™s the thing to think about. Donâ€™t worry about characters yet, donâ€™t worry about setting, donâ€™t even worry about plot. Think about something that you think is true. Write it down. Make it the truest thing in the world.</p>

<p>Write One True Sentence</p>

<p>You think you have problems writing? Imagine trying to write on this.</p>

<p>A Problem (and an Opportunity)</p>

<p>I know what youâ€™re thinking: grabbing people, and shaking them? They will hate me if I just go on a rant about â€˜the truthâ€™ like some crazy person. Thatâ€™s true. If we write a story thatÂ justÂ expresses our One True Sentence the story will be what we call â€˜preachyâ€™. Preachy is not fun because it abandons the core of storytelling - conflict. Thatâ€™s the problem.</p>

<p>But we arenâ€™t done yet. Thereâ€™s also an opportunity.</p>

<p>The Sentence of Doom</p>

<p>Now we have our One True Sentence, it should be easy to write down the exact opposite. Write the most evil thing you can think of. Write something False. Write a Sentence of Doom.</p>

<p>Now we are getting somewhere, because if our story shows One True Sentence in opposition to a Sentence of Doom then it will have conflict â€” and conflict is what stories are all about.</p>

<p>Personification</p>

<p>Robert McKee makes a good point at the end of the quote above â€” â€œprove your ideaâ€¦Â without explanationâ€. Thatâ€™s similar to the classic writing advice â€”Â show donâ€™t tell.Â </p>

<p>The One True Sentence doesnâ€™t go in the story, and neither does the Sentence of Doom.Â  Theyâ€™re something we write down and refer to. What we need to do is personify the conflict by introducing some characters.</p>

<p>We can use the archetypal characters fromÂ Archetypes that Make Your Story ResonateÂ to personify our story. Probably the Protagonist is on the side of Truth and the Antagonist is on the side of Falsehood. Or perhaps the story is more complicated? Itâ€™s up to you, but start thinking about how the characters can personify the conflict.</p>

<p>Plotting</p>

<p>So we have our One True Sentence, our Sentence of Doom, and our Archetypal Characters to personify both sides of the story. Now we can start to think about illustrating the conflict. To do that:</p>

<p>Something Happens</p>

<p>The something that happens is the plot.Â </p>

<p>Plot is a huge subject.Â Writing Spy Fiction with an Unputdownable Plotstarts to help us think of a plot.
Â 
Examples</p>

<p>Here are some examples of One True Sentence in spy fiction:</p>

<p>Thereâ€™s no moral high-ground in espionage.Â </p>

<p>The Spy Who Came in From the Cold, John le CarrÃ©</p>

<p>Wake up Britain! Germany is becoming a threat!</p>

<p>The Riddle of the SandsÂ , Erskine Childers</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>Spying is a ridiculous thing.
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Our Man in Havana, Graham Greene</p>

<p>Note two things:</p>
<ul>
  <li>The One True Sentence is never explicitly stated in those books (althoughThe Riddle of the SandsÂ comes pretty close). Their truth isÂ shown, notÂ told.</li>
  <li>You might not agree with any of those bookâ€™s One True Sentences, but thatâ€™s not the point. The authors believed them and set out to prove them.
Start Your Writing with One True Sentence</li>
</ul>

<p>So next time youâ€™re staring at a blank screen, or the wall, or out of the window, donâ€™t despair.Â </p>

<ul>
  <li>Think of something true.</li>
  <li>Write down that One True Sentence.</li>
  <li>Then start to think about how you can use storytelling techniques to illustrate that truth. How can you prove that truth to the world?
