<p>Three practical tips, two easy, one hard:</p>

<p>First,</p>

<p>Read everything you write aloud.Â </p>

<p>And when you come across anything that strikes you as well written by someone else, read that aloud too.</p>

<p>Nothing will improve your writing faster.</p>

<p>Why?</p>

<p>Because it will remind you that punctuation is for breaths, and paragraphs are for discrete units: a new idea, or a minor advance in an idea already in play.</p>

<p>It will show you when youâ€™re overwriting, because your mind is attuned to sound; you will hear yourself â€œgettingâ€ the point before the sentence is over.Â Â </p>

<p>Plus, running out of breath before you reach a punctuation mark isâ€“generally speakingâ€“a sign youâ€™ve overstuffed a phrase.</p>

<p>Also, if youâ€™re writing dialogue, it will instantly improve. The sound and your own familiarity with speaking will expose mistakes you missed reading silently.</p>

<p>If youâ€™re writing a speech, it will force you to consider pacing and toneâ€“something you can miss while quietly dreaming youâ€™re earthâ€™s finest orator.Â </p>

<p>Even if youâ€™re writing for an audience thatâ€™s going to read silently, this practice matters, if for no other reason than your readers have had many hours of speaking and listening to speech, so they will pick up on what seem like natural verbal cues, even when written.</p>

<p>But there is another reason; more on this in Item Threeâ€¦</p>

<p>Second,Â </p>

<p>If youâ€™re writing at a computer, make a second copy of the text, change the orientation of the page to Landscape, and hit enter after every period.</p>

<p>You will end up with a stack of sentences, one per line, with no space between.</p>

<p>Run your eyes down the left edge.Â </p>

<p>Does the same word keep popping up? A lot of youâ€™s, theâ€™s, heâ€™s, sheâ€™s, itâ€™s, theyâ€™s, Jimmyâ€™s or Cassandraâ€™s?Â </p>

<p>Do the sentences almost alwaysâ€“or invariablyâ€“start with a noun or a noun phrase? Is every sentence subject first, then predicate? Do any of them have commas or semicolons? Do they all have at least one comma? Are there loads of semicolons?</p>

<p>Now look at the lines abstractly, as if theyâ€™re drawn, not typed.</p>

<p>Are they all the same length? I mean literallyâ€“the length on the page, not the word count. When you step back from the page, does the print look like a perfect rectangle?</p>

<p>Now read each sentence as though it were a standalone, and not related to what precedes or follows.</p>

<p>Do they all work the same way? Do you have a stack of if-thens? Are they all descriptive? Is it a bunch of Intro: List constructions? Are they all images? Or abstractions? Do they all do the same job, so to speak?</p>

<p>Nowâ€¦</p>

<p>Iâ€™m not saying these repetitions are necessarily mistakes. If youâ€™re conscious youâ€™re committing to them, if youâ€™re doing them for an effect, okay.</p>

<p>But this is a great exercise for thinking structurally, exposing habits, and drawing your attention to what you might be missing when youâ€™re editing one sentence at a time while the words are in paragraphs.</p>

<p>Itâ€™s also a great exercise for taking every sentence (and ideally, every word) seriously. Both for its meaning and its order.</p>

<p>Why does this matter?</p>

<p>Because the eye gets bored with the same sentence lengths, paragraph widths, the same progressions, the same orders. If you donâ€™t vary sentence lengths or structures, or even opening words, youâ€™re sending this message to the readerâ€™s brain:Â </p>

<p>I didnâ€™t pay that much attention, so you donâ€™t have to either. A flash look at the next page, and youâ€™ll get the pattern: itâ€™s more of the same. Time to skim.</p>

<p>And with that, youâ€™ve lost your reader.</p>

<p>Varying sentences lengths, opening with different words, mixing the order of subjects and predicates and modifying clausesâ€“each in service to what youâ€™re trying to say, of courseâ€“sends a different signal to the readerâ€™s brain:</p>

<p>Iâ€™m like a great tour bus driverâ€“Iâ€™m in such command, you donâ€™t have to think about the driving. All you have to do is look out the window.Â </p>

<p>Now, readers arenâ€™t going think this consciously, but when someone says â€œthat person knows how to write,â€ well, guess whatâ€“a lot of it is mechanics that register subconsciously. And this exercise helps you convey that kind of command. Because, once again, youâ€™re paying attention to what the sentences are doing and how theyâ€™re doing it at a detailed level.Â </p>

<p>It will convey. You wouldnâ€™t believe how well.</p>

<p>Third,Â </p>

<p>Time for the Adult Swim advice:Â </p>

<p>Learn English prosody.</p>

<p>This means you should learn to accurately scan a line of metrical poetry, as well as find precisely where the stressed syllables (the beats) are in a sentence. And you should get good enough at it that you can scan the line without writing it down. Which means you can scan by ear.</p>

<p>This should take about 200 hours, all told. The good news is, thereâ€™s no rush, and a couple hours here and there counts. Might take a couple of years, but itâ€™s worth it.Â </p>

<p>And the work itself? You should know the iamb and dactyl in particular by sight and sound, know a substitution when you see or hear it, and you should be able to write 4-10 lines of blank verse (unrhymed, 10 syllables a line with 5 iambsâ€“also known as iambic pentameter) that sound natural in 30 minutes. The opposite of fancy, actually; like ordinary speech.</p>

<p>Why bother?</p>

<p>Because itâ€™s the secret to memorable writing. Even in prose.Â </p>

<p>Especially in prose.Â </p>

<p>If you know how to match impact words with beats in a sentence, you can write with tremendous power. The natural rhythm of English is the iamb (an unstressed syllable followed by a stressed syllable). If you can get three or four good ones in a row, youâ€™ve got a ballad-worthy line (a hell of a lot of song lyrics still depend on these lengths and this rhythm). You get to five iambs, and now youâ€™re on the court with Keats, Yeats, Shakespeare and Auden. Iâ€™m not saying youâ€™re as good. Iâ€™m saying youâ€™re using the same time-honored tools.</p>

<p>If you can add another 100 hours or so learning about assonance (vowel sound repetition) and interweaving repetitions of 2-3 vowel sounds in different combinations, your writing gathers even more power, just from technique alone.Â </p>

<p>Go find Evelyn Waugh, and read those gorgeous long sentences aloud; he knew prosody. Go scan Dylan Thomasâ€™s The FORCE that THROUGH the GREEN FUSE DRIVES the FLOWer, and there it is again: a normatively iambic run with substitutions, tails and headless iambsâ€“heâ€™s attacking the sound and rhythm to reinforce the attack of the subject matter. Thatâ€™s not just brainy, itâ€™s goosebump material. Read it aloud, and youâ€™ll hear.</p>

<p>Maybe you think this stuff is just for poetry.</p>

<p>Oh yeah?Â </p>

<p>Again, the natural English rhythm is the iamb.Â </p>

<p>da-DUM. Like a heartbeat.</p>

<p>toMORRow IS aNOTHer DAYâ€¦</p>

<p>you HAD me AT helLO.</p>

<p>Maybe you think it doesnâ€™t convey with silent reading.</p>

<p>Wrong again.Â </p>

<p>HOW GOES the NIGHT? Saint GILESâ€™s CLOCK is STRIKing NINE. The weather is dull and wet, and the long lines of street lamps are blurred, as if we saw them through tears. A DAMP wind BLOWS and TAKES the PIEmanâ€™s FIRE out, when he opens the door of his little furnace, carrying away an eddy of sparks.</p>

<p>Charles Dickens. Iambic runs tucked in a prose paragraph.Â </p>

<p>That second sentence? Perfect iambic tetrameter.Â </p>

<p>Not an accident.Â </p>

<p>Itâ€™s a technique. It works because iambic runs sing. Not an exaggeration: the word sonnet derives from song, and that form lives and dies with iambs.Â  Theyâ€™reâ€¦pretty. And readers sense them, even reading silently.Â </p>

<p>You learn to spot iambic runs, and youâ€™ll catch great writers from Melville to DeLillo working this technique all over the place. Dactyls, spondees and trochees too, all with different effects when repeated two, three, four, five and six times. Or when theyâ€™re subbed in for the expected foot in a run with a different normative rhythm. Itâ€™s not a trick, itâ€™s an inherent element in the language.Â </p>

<p>And hey, you speak and write English. So you can do this too. You can learn it. You can. You want to write with all the power you can muster, this is where you need to go.</p>

<p>THIS is WHERE you NEED to GO</p>

<p>â€¦headless iamb/iamb/iamb/iambâ€¦iambic tetrameter, a singsong rhythm that aids memory, especially with simple wordsâ€¦a formal phrase ending a sentence that opened with a free verse (prose) phraseâ€¦no rhythm then rhythmâ€¦disorder then orderâ€¦suggestion then resultâ€¦intro then payoffâ€¦an encapsulation of the third point in one sentence to close out the argument, and a beat falls on the the last word, a verb from childhood, with a subtext of playing, a one-syllable call to action, and the sound of an open-ended vowel:Â </p>

<p>â€œgo.â€Â </p>

<p>It works. Itâ€™s happening all around you right now. The reading brain is smarter than you think; subconsciously, itâ€™s picking up a lot of this already.Â </p>

<p>A little study, and youâ€™ll see it all.</p>

