<p>But in person Derek could be raucous, silly. Once, after I had recited Audenâ€™s â€œThe Fall of Romeâ€ during his office hours, Derek said, â€œMy god! Are you chewing gum? That was like an audition for â€˜Guys and Dolls.â€™ â€œ At the Mexican restaurant where I showed him my pages about Kenneth Koch, Derek joked with the waitress, who had announced that the special was cactus soup. â€œAre there prickles in it?â€ he asked. English wasnâ€™t her native language, and she wasnâ€™t sure what he was asking. She said, twice, â€œIâ€™m sorry, sir, we donâ€™t have pickles on the menu.â€ He asked again, â€œAre there prickles in the cactus soup?â€ And she said, â€œNo, no pickles,â€ and he asked, â€œWhat if there are?â€ I was too shy to correct or translate, but finally the waitress smiled. â€œIf there are pickles, you wonâ€™t have to pay.â€ Derek, delighted, ordered a bowl of soup for each of us.Â Â Once, over a different meal, Derek turned to me and asked if I was â€œactually Jewish.â€ It was possible to be Jewish, he told me, but not Jewish enough; black, but not black enough. When I asked enough for what, he told me, â€œto be clear.â€ At the time, I thought, Who wants that? But Derek knew that, on some level, we all do. He spent his life in exile, writing the islands, painting the sea with watercolor as well as words; he was an outsider, an insider, a citizen of the global South, a black man in the Northeast. In 2007, the colicky critic William Logan wrote a harsh review of Walcottâ€™s â€œSelected Poems,â€ suggesting that Walcottâ€™s work was shallow and conceited, the reflections of an invented persona. Indignant at the attack on our mentor, my friend the poet Kirun Kapur and I werenâ€™t sure exactly how to set the record right, only that we had to try. We stayed up late crafting a letter to the editor, explaining how Walcottâ€™s poems captured the experience of an entire generation in exile, how it showed that individuals can be made of more than one place, how it reflec