<p>the three biggies</p>

<p>Beginners often need to learn three things:Â     (1) write every day;    (2) read everything you write out loud;Â     (3) and make multiple drafts.    Almost every writing book makes these suggestions, but when I first started writing, I refused to follow them. Why? Because I was egotistical and lazy. I thought maybeÂ otherÂ writers needed to write every day, but surelyÂ IÂ didnâ€™t need to. Besides, it was too much work. And I felt the same way about reading aloud and making multiple drafts.Â   Writing well isÂ hard. You need to practice every day, because itâ€™s the only way youâ€™ll improveâ€”and you can easily backslide. So you need to â€œpractice scales,â€ like a pianist.Â   If you canâ€™t think of anything to write today, just describe your morning: â€œThe alarm went off. I groaned and refused to get out of bed. But it kept ringing, so finally I threw the covers aside and stumbled to the bathroomâ€¦â€ It doesnâ€™t matter what you write. It doesnâ€™t have to be interesting. You donâ€™t need to show it to anyone. Just write, write, writeâ€¦   You donâ€™t get to call yourself a writer unless you write every day. But if you write every day, youâ€™re an official writer, even if youâ€™ve never had anything published.   You need to readÂ everythingÂ youâ€™ve written out loud, because thatâ€™s the only way youâ€™ll know if it sounds natural. As soon as I mouth my words, I find all sorts of forced and awkward-sounding passages. (TIP: if youâ€™re at work or a coffee shop and canâ€™t read out loud, at least move your lips. It will force your brain to imagine youâ€™re reading out loud.)    You have to make multiple drafts because editing is easier than writing. And you need to first get something down on paper so youÂ haveÂ something to edit. Think of your first draft as a data dump. Then you start chiseling away at it, going over each word, adding and subtracting.Â     Stephen King, F. Scott Fitzgerald, Jane Austen â€¦ they all work (or worked) with multiple drafts. I