<p>PS. You donâ€™t have writerâ€™s block! SeeÂ Marcus Geduldâ€™s answer to How can I deal with writerâ€™s block when I have so many ideas in my head, but no way to write them down?    And keep in mind what Ira Glass has to say about taste (emphasis added): <br />
   Nobody tells this to people who are beginners, I wish someone told me. All of us who do creative work, we get into it because we have good taste.
     But there is this gap. For the first couple years you make stuff, itâ€™s just not that good. Itâ€™s trying to be good, it has potential, but itâ€™s not. But your taste, the thing that got you into the game, is still killer. And your taste is why your work disappoints you. A lot of people never get past this phase, they quit.
     Most people I know who do interesting, creative work went through years of this. We know our work doesnâ€™t have this special thing that we want it to have. We all go through this. And if you are just starting out or you are still in this phase, you gotta know its normal and the most important thing you can do is do a lot of work.
     Put yourself on a deadline so that every week you will finish one story.Â It is only by going through a volume of work that you will close that gap, and your work will be as good as your ambitions.
     Â And I took longer to figure out how to do this than anyone Iâ€™ve ever met. Itâ€™s gonna take awhile. Itâ€™s normal to take awhile. Youâ€™ve just gotta fight your way through.</p>

<p>every piece of writing counts</p>

<p>If you want to be a writer, you should always be â€œon.â€ Give up the idea of â€œtossed off writing thatâ€™s not real writing.â€ Proof-read and redraft your emails, your text messages, your shopping lists.Â If youâ€™re a writer, you care about writing.Â You always care. You alwaysÂ takeÂ care.    The flip version of this â€œlawâ€ is: you know youâ€™re a writer when you start proof-reading your text messages, worrying over each wordâ€”when you can no-longer conceive of not caring how you write a sentence.Â     Do you know any professional chefs? I do. They donâ€™t say, â€œI know Iâ€™m a chef, but Iâ€™m just making a sandwich for a snack.â€ They areÂ incapableÂ of being around food without caring. When they are around food, they care.Â  <br />
