<p>E-Prime, a constrained English, forbids you to use any form of the verb â€œto be,â€ so instead of writing, â€œSheÂ wasÂ scared,â€ you must write, â€œShe shiveredâ€ or â€œShe ran screaming to her mother.â€ I spent a year writing in e-prime (always working to make my prose sound natural, despite the constraint), allowing myself to use â€œto beâ€ forms only in quotes, as in this paragraph. E-prime forces you to craft every sentence around an agentÂ doingÂ something, e.g. a woman shivering, a dog peeing, or a bomb exploding. My e-prime year improved my writing more than any other exercise.Â  <br />
break a rule</p>

<p>Youâ€™ve heard teachers say, â€œYou have to know the rules before you can break them.â€ Okay, well: you know the rules. So now go ahead and smash them to pieces. You may not be a grammarian, but you know at least some rules of writing. Those are the ones youâ€™re allowed to break, and those are the ones youÂ mustÂ break.    Why? Because writers donâ€™t let words own or dominate them. WritersÂ ownwords. Writers hypnotize nouns and order them to act like verbs; they gleefully stick square pegs in round holes; they spit in the eyes of their fifth-grade English teachers.    I am not excusing shoddy, lazy work. What I am saying is this: if you donâ€™t know the rules, the words control you. If youâ€™re controlled by the rules, the wordsÂ stillÂ control you. You must become the master of the words and the rules, using them as tools, not as bosses.Â     Obviously, if youâ€™re a student and writing â€œainâ€™tâ€ will get you an F, donâ€™t do it. But in your own writing, be the boss and donâ€™t let anyone else push you around.Â     Unless youâ€™re writing experimental poetry or prose (or colloquial dialogue), go easy on the departures from standard English. They should be the spice, not the main course. If every word is surprising, none of them are surprising. The eccentric is only effective when itâ€™s hidden within the ordinary.Â     You donâ€™t have to keep all your experiments. Youâ€™re also in control over what goes into the final draft. Just keep playing. Keep loose with language.Â     â€œMy Lit professor assignedÂ Romeo and Juliet,Â Hamlet, andÂ Othello, and now my brain is totally Shakespeared, and I donâ€™t know whether to be or not to be.â€    â€œShe ordered me to get her lunch, then she made me fix the toilet, then she told me to wash all the dishes, then she ordered me to drive her mom to the airport, then she gribbled me to grickle her grapper grouper until I smashed her head with a doodle doodle doo!â€ <br />
