  <li>â€œThis Perfect Dayâ€ by Ira Levin and â€œThe Queenâ€™s Gambitâ€ by Walter Tevis. I am lumping these together, because, for my money, they are the perfect genre novels. Levinâ€™s book is a sci-fi dystopia, somewhat like â€œLoganâ€™s Run,â€ and Tevisâ€™s book is basically a sports story, with chess being the sport. Neither has any pretension of being high art, but both are gems, crafted with simple, confident prose and genius plotting. Iâ€™d like to give a shout-out here to Levinâ€™s mystery novel, â€œA Kiss Before Dying,â€ which is impossible to film, though several people have tried and failed.</li>
