<p>Write because you have to.
If you donâ€™t have to, donâ€™t write. Because â€¦ you donâ€™t have to.
Donâ€™t write because you want to be a writer. Writers donâ€™t write because they want to be writers; they write because they have to.
Donâ€™t write because you want to make money as a writer. Very few writers earn a living writing. Money is nice if you wind up getting it, but the real reason to write is because you have to.
If you have to write, and you do write (every single day, without exception!)Â andÂ you work on your craftâ€”on pacing, prose mechanics, metaphors, grammar, clarity, sensuality, etc.â€”then thereâ€™s a good chance your writing will improve to the point that others will start noticing it.
Write every day. Make multiple drafts. Research. Edit what you write. Labor over every word.
Oh, and if youâ€™re a writer, then youâ€™re always switched on, whenever you write. Thereâ€™s no distinction between the the important writing you do and the tossed-off stuff, because, since youÂ haveÂ to write, and since you care deeply about words, even a shopping list deserves your precision and scrutiny.
Donâ€™t write because you want a Quora T-shirt; donâ€™t write because you want to be one of the cool kids. Donâ€™t write because you want people to notice you. Write because you have to.
I write because I have to. I canâ€™t think clearly unless I write. Unless I describe a situation in words, itâ€™s as if it never happened to me. I have to write in order to fix my world, in order to stop it from spinning into a confused muddle of arbitrary giraffes and pipe cleaners.
Aside from the fact that my writing is (hopefully) always improving, I write exactly the same way, and the same amount, as I did before I became a Top Writer. And if Quora takes my quill away, Iâ€™ll continue writing the same way and the same amount.
I appreciate the honor, but I donâ€™t write to be a Top Writer; I write because I have to.
Which is why IÂ amÂ a Top Writer.
None of the Top Writers I know tried to become Top Writers.
PS. Youâ€™re not anÂ aspiringÂ writer. Never call yourself that again! Youâ€™re either a writer or youâ€™re not. Maybe youâ€™re not aÂ publishedÂ writer. So what? Plenty of famous writers werenâ€™t published (or were published and then forgotten) during their lifetimes. Many good and great writers never get published.
Maybe youâ€™re not aÂ paidÂ writer. Many published writers donâ€™t get paid are barely paid. I know one who made 36 cents on her first book, and it wasnâ€™t a vanity project: it was put out by a well-known publisher!
Maybe youâ€™re a bad or mediocre writer (who will, hopefullyâ€”with lots of hard workâ€”improve over time), but a bad writer is still a writer. If you devote yourself to writing, write ever day, and toil at your craft, then (good or bad, paid or unpaid, published or not), youâ€™re a writer; if you donâ€™t do those things, youâ€™re not.
Because a writer is someone who writes.
Step one: call yourself a writer.
Step two: write.
Step three: repeat steps two and three.</p>

<hr />

<p>Five things: 1. By developing a deep love of language. This mostly happened through constant reading. I only read books by writers who care about language.Â  2. By spending years writing every day and, each time, laboring over the language. (Trying to make it as good as the language in the great books I was reading.) 3. By learning how to type really fast. I didnâ€™t really enjoy writing until I was able to type almost as fast as I could think. When the physical act of writing slowed me down, I was spending more time being aggravated about that than focusing on the words I was using. (I learned to type fast by writing a book. By the time I was done, my fingers were flying over the keyboard.) 4. By reading aloud everything I write. 5. By assuming everything my teachers told me about writing was bullshit.</p>

