<p>Jon Ronson on writing fiction
From an Interview with Jon Ronson, in which he was asked about a screenplay heâ€™d written:</p>

<p>[Have you written other fiction?]</p>

<p>No, first time. At first, I just couldnâ€™t get my head around it. You know, what we do, whatever happens at this table is our material. But in a movie, you go into a restaurant, you sit down, and thereâ€™s fucking nobody there. The restaurant doesnâ€™t exist. Itâ€™s like a big white space, and that completely sort of fucked with my mind, because I was thinking, well, thereâ€™s nothing to tell me what is acceptable for this script and what is not acceptable. Like in journalism, whatâ€™s acceptable is what actually happened, and whatâ€™s not acceptable is what didnâ€™t happen. But with fiction, nothing happened, so you have to make these kind of complete judgments on what would the character do that? And itâ€™s like, you could say, yeah, of course the character would do that, because this character doesnâ€™t exist, so he could do fucking anything. He can go up to space, he can do anything.</p>

<p>So that completely screwed me with me for about two years. This was like a five-year process. Then after awhile, these characters start to form, and you do start to think, okay, I know enough about [the characters] to sort of know what they would or wouldnâ€™t rationally do in a situation. So the further into the process you get, the more it actually feels like journalism. Because the stuff youâ€™ve written does exist and then that informs the rest of it. So the second half of the process was actually really similar to journalism and I really liked it a lot. I donâ€™t know whether I could do it again.</p>

<p>â€“ â€œSilly, Funny Stories About Really Serious Thingsâ€: A Chat With Writer Jon Ronson</p>

<p>And hereâ€™s a similar quote, from Lawrence Weschler on why he doesnâ€™t write fiction:</p>

<p>[T]he part of my sensibility which I demonstrate in nonfiction makes fiction an impossible mode for me. Thatâ€™s because for me the world is already filled to bursting with interconnections, interrelationships, consequences, and consequences of consequences. The world as it is is overdetermined: the web of all those interrelationships is dense to the point of saturation. Thatâ€™s what my reporting becomes about: taking any single knot and worrying out the threads, tracing the interconnections, following the mesh through into the wider, outlying mesh, establishing the proper analogies, ferreting out the false strands. If I were somehow to be forced to write a fiction about, say, a make-believe Caribbean island, I wouldnâ€™t know where to put it, because the Caribbean as it is is already fullâ€“â€“-thereâ€™s no room in it for any fictional islands. Dropping one in there would provoke a tidal wave, and all other places would be swept away.</p>

<p>â€“ Mark Athitakisâ€™ American Fiction Notes</p>

